\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>When a man achieves a major <-/fete> the first ti
me, you may call it a fluke. <#/>But when he does it the second time, you give him a second look. <#/>The theatre fraternity is looking at Ben Ateku, the co-ordinator of the Nairobi Theatre Academy. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Ateku was recently declared winner of the 1992 British Broadcasting Corporation <-/playwriting> competition in the Theatre Africa series. 
\par <#/>In 1988, Ateku was one of the six winners out of 120 contestants. <#/>His entry then was a play titled <-_called> }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Tom Says He is Dead}{\fs24\lang2057 , based on the breakdown of the extended family system. 
\par <#/>This time round, Ateku has done it with }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Street People}{\fs24\lang2057 , originally a stage play composed in 1989 and staged by Wazalendo Players, but now adopted into a radio script for the competition. 
\par <#/>The October to December issue of the BBC's }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Focus on Africa Magazine}{\fs24\lang2057 
 carries excerpts of the play as a supplement to herald the Africa theatre season which starts on November 21 at 7.30 pm with the airing of Ateku's play and a repeat on November 22 at 4.30 am, 6.30 am and 6.30 pm. 
\par <#/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Street People}{\fs24\lang2057  is a hilarious play revolving round Johny and Jimmy, street urchins who are bent of }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>prep}{\fs24\lang2057  making a buck by any means. 
\par <#/>After robbing a street walker of a briefcase which turns out to contain worthless paper, they masquerade as traffic police
men and manage to get some bribes, including some from the wife of the police commissioner who is driving with a licence expiring "next year" and - contrary to their rules - in the rain. 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>They decide to get into street preaching in a most comical manne
r. <#/>As the Reverends Wilson (Jimmy) and Motherson (Johny), they inform the congregation that they have just arrived on foot from Judah, and that is why they look shabby. 
