\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Kenya's educational system, like other systems in developing countries, lays great emphasis on academic excellence, sometimes at the expense of the development of thinking and reasoning skills. 
\par <#/>And in an attempt to meet standards that put glory and glamour - almost everything that matters in life - on academic certificates many students have wallowed in
 classrooms with ignored talents, reading day in day out just to pass examinations and later qualify as impractical, illiterate graduates or as unemployable (unemployed) drop-outs. 
\par <#/>But in Nairobi one institution which seems to have weathered the academic-certificates mania is the Nairobi Theatre Academy (NTA), and }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
institution that aims at harnessing and developing theatrical skills. 
\par <#/>According to Ben Ateku, the co-ordinator, the academy does not have a set minimum academic requirement for interested applicants. <#/>It is more interesting in identifying potential talent and commitment. 
\par <#/>However, the academy is keen to judge the intellectual capabilities of applicants. <#/>This ensures that able people are admitted, academic excellence n
otwithstanding, and helps fight stereotyped attitudes that glorify academic excellence at the expense of other skills and talents. 
\par <#/>The NTA was inaugurated on March 30, 1990, and is sponsored by the French Government through the French Cultural Centre. <#/>Its offices and auditorium are on the third floor of the FCC along Loita Street in Nairobi. 
\par <#/>The principle aim of its forming it was to promote theatre in Kenya by acting as the umbrella organisation joining together aspiring artistes from different theatre groups in a bid to share and sharpen skills. 
\par <#/>Initially, the academy started its programmes by conducting theatre workshops and performing plays. <#/>Since its formation, the academy has performed several plays, including }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Aikin Mata}{\fs24\lang2057 ,}{\i\fs24\lang2057 
 The Imaginary Invalid, The Vow and An Exchange for Honour}{\fs24\lang2057 
, among others. <#/>In 1991, which was its second year of existence, the academy intensified its programmes and developed a one-year theatre education curriculum. <#/>Currently, it has 52 students of whom 31 are part-time and 21 full-time. 
\par <#/>Courses are
 conducted every term like in schools. <#/>The full-time classes begin at 10 am and end at 5 pm while the part-time classes begin at 5.30 pm and end at 7.30 pm. <#/>Part-time students pay fees while full-time students are unemployed and are given a small 
allowance which enables them to meet travelling costs. 
\par <#/>When the course was advertised, 206 people applied, but the academy was able to admit a mere 62. <#/>This is evidence that the programme is popular in Kenya. 
\par <#/>"The course started in early September, 1990, and the progress so far is commendable," says Ateku. 
\par <#/>What about varying commentaries from different theatre critics? <#/>Ateku says such commentaries are more often than not subjective. <#/>An artiste should not base his motivation on critiques, }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{
\fs24\lang2057 The drive to creativity should come from within and artistes should soberly judge each critic individually so that they can tell the difference between constructive and destructive criticism. <#/>The academy hopes to continue intensifying 
its theatre courses, develop and document them for posterity. 
\par <#/>Lecturers come from the literature departments of our universities. <#/>Experienced actors and theatre directors and writers also teach and are paid on a part-time basis. 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>As regards al
legations by critics that the academy has veered from its intended objectives, he says this is false. <#/>Critics lay emphasis on production, ignoring other aspects of training at the academy. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 "The biggest challenge has been to come up with a theatre 
curriculum relevant to Kenya artistes. <#/>The continuous workshops did not meet objectives adequately. <#/>We have now developed a relevant curriculum. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Also, the response of theatre fans was rather discouraging and it was difficult to have a full house," says Ateku}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par }{\v\fs24\lang2057 
The academy did not meet the censor's scythe. On requirements that anyone intending to start a theatre group must be cleared at Nyayo House, Ateku as one of the founder members of Wazalendo Players, feels that this censorship will kill Kenyan theatre.

\par Artistes need a lot of support from the relevant authorities and this requirement will be a big burden on them.
\par On the general feeling, that <-/threatre> charges averaging Sh50, are too high for the common man, Ateku says this is untrue. Production
 of a good play takes about six weeks and the cost of hiring facilities, equipment and reimbursing fares are quite high. A production should be able to sustain itself and since many firms are not willing to sponsor plays, charges have to be fixed to cover
 the costs.
\par Besides the training programme, the academy hopes to launch a staff development programme in future. Theatre fans and NTA enthusiasts should continue supporting the academy in all its new endeavours.
\par "Artistes should view arts with the seriousness it deserves," Ateku says.
\par Does the academy have plans to solicit funds for scholarships to budding artistes in Kenya? The possibility exists and the current subsidized programme is such an initiative.
\par Apart from the annual play <-/wrighting> competition, the NTA will identify other areas where it may encourage people sharpen to their talents.
\par The NTA liaises with other theatre groups and educational institutions who hire their costumes. "We train members of other theatre groups who eventually transfer th
e skills to their respective groups. We liaise with the American Cultural Centre and the British Council. Schools approach us to hold workshops for them. Generally the response is encouraging," says Ateku.
\par Ateku calls upon all Kenyan theatre fans to come o
ut and watch plays performed by amateur groups to encourage them. Kenyans in general should appreciate what theatre can do for them, apart from entertainment value. "They should look out for the overall impact that theatre can make on their lives," he say
s. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
