\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 For more than a decade, his characteristic deep quivering voice and animation-chants of "<ea_>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Moreno aye mabe - Moreno amekasilika<ea/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
! <#/>" ruled the air-waves. <#/>Many radio listeners and DJs found his songs irresistible. <#/>He had the same cutting edge on the local charts in which - from his 1981 hit-songs }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Dunia ni Duara}{\fs24\lang2057  and }{\i\fs24\lang2057 
Pili Mswahili}{\fs24\lang2057 , to his 1993 blockbuster }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Vidonge Sitaki}{\fs24\lang2057  - he appeared on the hit parade with a frequency that had many musicians turning green with envy. 
\par <#/>The death 10 days ago of the Kenya-based Zairean musician, Batamba Wenda Morris, a man many knew simply as Moreno, brings to a sudden halt one of the most illustrious recording career in recent times. 
\par <#/>Moreno, who arrived in Kenya two decades ago, married a Kenyan, Anna Wangui, and had two children, died at his home in Dandora Estate, Nairobi. <#/>Early last month, he cut short a three-month tour in D
ubai because of ill-health and returned to Kenya leaving behind his long-time colleague, Koko Zigo Mike, and other musicians who are still performing there. 
\par <#/>Moreno mainly <-_sung><+_sang> in Kiswahili and the themes of his songs varied from social commentaries like }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Dunia ni Duara}{\fs24\lang2057 , }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mapenzi ya Shinda}{\fs24\lang2057  and }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mwanamke}{
\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Hatosheki}{\fs24\lang2057 , to love songs like }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Angela}{\fs24\lang2057  and }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Pili}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mswahili}{\fs24\lang2057 . 
\par <#/>This last was a song about his girlfriend, Pili Mikendo Kassim, a Tanzanian model he met in 1976 while with Orchestra Les Noirs in Mombasa. 
\par <#/>Born in Kisangani, Haut. <#/>Zaire Province of Zaire in 1955, Moreno quit school in 1971 to join Orchestra Marquis Sasa Bata. <#/>He later entered Uganda and in 1974 joined Orchestra Bana Ngenge of Jojo Ikomo, with which he travelled to Nairobi. 

\par <#/>When the group broke up in 1976, Moreno and Ikomo were among the musicians who joined Orchestra Les Noirs, an outfit led by Kalembi Mukaputu "Kajos." 
\par <#/>Ikomo and Kajos were to join TP OK Jazz later. <#/>Today, they play with Pepe Kale and Madilu 
System Bialu respectively. <#/>In the early and mid-Seventies, many Zairean groups and musicians left their motherland for West and East Africa. <#/>Some headed for Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, which they used as a spring board to France and Belgium. <#/>In th
is group were Sam Mangwana and Lokassa ya Mbongo, and their African All Stars outfit. 
\par <#/>Another group crossed into Kenya through Uganda. <#/>It was the era when groups like Boma Liwanza of Shango Lola, Les Kinois of Samba Mapangala, Les Mangelepa of the 
now born-again Bwammy wa Lumwona, and Super Mazembe of Lonwa Didos had the "City in the Sun" reverberating with sounds and dance styles hitherto unknown in <-_Kenyan><+_Kenya>. 
\par <#/>In 1978, Moreno left Les Noirs and headed for Dar-es-Salaam where he played with Orchestra Safari Sound and later, Kiauri Voice, before returning to Nairobi in 1980. 
\par <#/>On arrival, Babu Shah Megs and Nderitu Munene discovered Moreno as "an untapped talent with a lot of potential. <#/>I was particularly impressed with}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>prep}{\fs24\lang2057 
 his command of Kiswahili at a time when "local" Zaireans spoke broken Kiswahili and most seemed to think it beneath them to speak it, let alone sing in it. <#/>" says Megs. 
