), introduced in 1973, however, remained a preserve of a few interested students. <#/>Out of 40,624 candidates who sat for the East African Certificate of Education (EACE) examination in 1974, a meagre 5,009 sat for the <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Fasihi}{
\fs24\lang2057  paper! 
\par <#/>Ironically, the English language continued to enjoy prominence as a compulsory subject at the EACE examination besides being the language of instruction in all other subjects. <#/>This background explains why many literate Kenyans today - even univers
ity graduates - cannot confidently speak or write grammatical Kiswahili. <#/>Yet most of them can beat the Englishman in his own language! 
\par <#/>We can now guess why there are very few authentic Kiswahili novels by Kenyan authors. <#/>The dismal results of this marginalisation of Kiswahili are now glaring: We are compelled to turn to Tanzanian authors for virtually all <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 
Fasihi}{\fs24\lang2057  <-/setbooks> in the KCSE examination. 
\par <#/>Of the four texts to be examined from next year, three - }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Kusadikika}{\fs24\lang2057  by Shaaban Robert; }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Mashetani}{\fs24\lang2057  by Ebrahim Hussein and }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Kisima cha Giningi}{\fs24\lang2057 
 by Mohammed Said Abdulla - are authored by Tanzanians. <#/>The fourth, }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Masaibu ya Ndugu Jero}{\fs24\lang2057 , is a translation of Wole Soyinka's }{\i\fs24\lang2057 The Trials of Brother Jero}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>No Kenyan-authored book is to be examined in the Kenyan examination! 
\par <#/>In fact, Tanzanian authors, like Ebrahim Hussein, Mohammed Suleiman Mohammed, Mohammed Said Abdulla and Said Ahamed Mohammed, have dominated Kenya's <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Fasihi}{\fs24\lang2057  syllabus for a long time. 
\par <#/>One finds an easy explanation fo
r this. <#/>For Tanzania, Kiswahili is both an official and national language which has been adopted as the language of instruction in the country's system of education. <#/>Kiswahili has become part and parcel of Tanzania's total system such that a Kenya
n who is heard to speak fluent Kiswahili is often said to speak it "like a Tanzanian". 
