\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Does transparency exist in book publishing corridors? }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Kenyan publishers have often come under sharp criticism for allegedly continuing to publish old writers while shutting out budding ones. 
\par <#/>But publishers are unanimous that good authors have become an endangered species. 
\par <#/>There is hardly any new writer who is turning out a "publishable" manuscript. 
\par <#/>However, budding writers are relentlessly expressing bitterness over what they see as the publishers' bias for old names. 
\par <#/>"Any work out of the ordinary presented by a new writer is promptly slapped with a rejection slip. <#/>Meanwhile, they welcome manuscripts from old writers, however shoddy," argued Evans Kinyua. 
\par <#/>This angry voice might paint the wrong picture that there is no "transparency" in the publishing industry. 
\par <#/>It suggests that all professional ethics have been shelved and subjectivity reigns supreme in the publishing corridors. 
\par <#/>Far from it. <#/>Any manuscript on any subject is given a fair assessment by the publisher's assessment regardless of its author. <#/>After a preliminary assessment, an editor can tell a potential manuscript from an "unpublishable" one. 
\par <#/>Most manuscripts which are too poor do not go beyond this state. <#/>They are returned to the authors with a covering letter detailing weaknesses and possible amendments. 
\par <#/>A potential manuscript is assessed in-house first and then the editor commissions at least two external readers who are well versed in the subject matter. 
\par <#/>Any information in the script which might reveal the author's identity is sealed to ensure an objective assessment. <#/>Therefore, there is little room that an assessor will know whether the author is "old" or "new". 
\par <#/>The assessment addresses several aspects; appropriateness of subject matter, language problems (grammar and syntax), target audience, plagiarism, possible competition, dexterity for details, logical development of ideas and communicative power. 

\par <#/>When all assessment reports have been assembled, the manuscript's fate is then determined by an editorial board on the basis of the reports. 
\par <#/>It may be rejected unconditionally, rejected with <-/sugestions> for improvement or accepted with suggestions for revision. 
\par <#/>In all cases, the author is availed copies of the assessment reports and is at liberty to seek a follow-up discussion as many times as it has been amended. 
\par <#/>The publisher meets all the costs of assessment, editing, typesetting, illustrations, design, printing, marketing and distribution of the author's work. 
\par <#/>The author does not pay even a cent. <#/>In fact he stands to earn a royalty for as long as his book is in circulation. <#/>He might even successfully bargain for an advance royalty before his work is published. 
\par <#/>It is therefore evident that maximum objectivity and <-/fairplay> obtains in the publishing industry. <#/>If there are any cases of
 "old" names which have been consistently published, it is because they have consistently turned out powerful manuscripts which cry for publication. 
\par <#/>Potential authors are welcome any time to seek all manner of advice from publishers. <#/>These incentives and motivators are only available to those who show interest. 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>No publisher is obliged to publish a manuscript that will only end up accumulating dust in the warehouse just because a potential author must be motivated. 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The publisher, being a b
usinessman, identifies needs through market research, develops the product, invests in its production and distribution with the aim of recovering financial investment from sales turn-over. 
\par <#/>If publishers have been seen to mainly publish educational books, it is because that is where the market is. <#/>Publishers have to sustain their existence by breaking even. 
\par <#/>Like any businessman, they aim at satisfying the market needs at a profit. <#/>They stand to be blamed if they claim to publish yet they cannot service the society's educational system. 
