\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 In many parts of the world, leaders come and go. <#/>Not in Afr
ica. <#/>African leaders are "live presidents", either overtly or covertly. <#/>The one thing the African citizen is for ever exposed to is the exhortation by political surrogates that he is lucky to live where he lives. 
\par <#/>The African head of state is a
 very mysterious being. <#/>He is an all-knowing, benevolent father of the nation. <#/>There is absolutely nothing he does not know. <#/>He is simply a fountain of knowledge and wisdom. <#/>Those who live in his country should be thankful that God placed 
t
hem there and gave them such a wise and God-fearing leader, who ostensibly goes by the name "His Excellency", "Father of the Nation" or "Philosopher". <#/>The ridiculous nature of such <-/mysterisms> has, fortunately, not always been lost to all African c
itizens. <#/>At least not to Malawi's Tiyambe Zeleza, as is manifest in his new book, }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Smouldering Charcoal}{\fs24\lang2057 . 
\par <#/>This is the long, sad tale of an African nation in the suffocating grip of a <-/tyranical> leader. <#/>In this un-named state, Our Leader reigns supreme. <#/>Everyone must toe Our Leader's line or quit.<X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
In this fast-moving 192 pager, Zeleza chronicles the pithy tribulations of ordinary people under a frightful dictator who mystifies himself as the most altruistic leader there ever was.
\par Mchere is a factory hand at the largest bakery in the country. Although he toils very hard for his employer, Mchere and his colleagues hardly earn enough to buy a loaf of bread a day throughout the month. They live in sub-human conditions in slum houses w
hich they share with rats or other lesser creatures.
\par They can hardly feed their children, pay for their medical care or take them to school. When they ask for better remuneration through properly laid-down channels, the authorities subject them to the most 
dehumanising conditions in prison torture-chambers. They have failed to appreciate all the good Our Leader and his government are doing to industrialise the country. They are on the payroll of foreign masters.
\par Dambo is what is popularly referred to as a "h
uman rights lawyer". His incessant criticisms of the regime leads to his being mysteriously murdered and his body dumped into a city river. His wife is rusticated to his home village because "she is the wife of a dissident".
\par Chola, a prolific journalist, i
s detained without trial when, both deeply sorrowful of the murder of his friend Dambo and fed up of churning out nonsensical propaganda in praise of Our Leader, he is betrayed by his houseboy as he tries to flee into exile. In the corridors of silence in
 detention, he is tortured to death. His body is suspended from a piece of cloth in his cell to cheat the world that he committed suicide.
\par Such are some of the painful personal stories that make this
 trenchant story of a country where The Party is a frightful monster that invades the people's lives to the innermost corners of their bedrooms. The Party grows in stature to such the point that every little sphere of any individual's life is determined b
y how he relates to it. Party-mania leads to a pathetic and pathological state where culprits can be created overnight.
\par In a situation that is reminiscent of the notorious Joseph McCarthy witch-hunting for "communists" in America early this century, persona
l scores are settled in the name of The Party. The moment one crosses the line of a party official, he is accused of subverting The Party and His Excellency Our Leader.
\par In any case, the demarcation between The Party, the Government and Our Leader is not clear at all!
\par As soon as you cross their path, woe betide you. You will lose your job, business licence, friends, spouse - anything that gives you a semblance of security and human dignity.
\par Although Zeleza has not named the country against which this story i
s cast, the storyline in very many ways conjures up the <-/>the picture of Malawi under the crackpot iron-fist of Dr Kamuzu Banda. Apart from the fact that <-/Zelaza> was born in colonial exile and continues to live there even after independence, one cann
o
t fail to see in this story the kind of fate that has befallen the likes of poet Jack Mapanje, who was detained without trial, Otton and Vera Chirwa, who were captured outside Malawi and dragged into Malawi to be condemned to death for opposing Banda's au
tocracy, and the millions of Malawians who now live in exile from where they are applying pressure to get rid of Banda.
\par Zeleza's book is simply compulsory reading for every citizen of Africa. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
